  "description": "Add a frontend-only 'Pacing Meter' to the Conversation page that gives the learner immediate feedback on their speaking pace during a reply turn. While the user is recording (speech recognition active in frontend/src/pages/Conversation.tsx), display a small horizontal gauge with three zones (slow <100 wpm = blue, natural 100-160 wpm = green, rushed >160 wpm = orange) and a moving needle showing the current live words-per-minute computed from the in-progress transcript and elapsed time. After the user submits the turn, show a one-line coaching tip beneath the input ('Nice natural pace ✨', 'Try slowing down for clarity', or 'You can speak a touch faster — sounded hesitant') based on the final WPM, and remember the last 5 WPM values in localStorage to render a tiny sparkline of pacing trend across turns within the same session.\n\nImplementation: create a new component frontend/src/components/conversation/ReplyPacingMeter.tsx that takes props { transcript: string, isRecording: boolean, startedAt: number | null, recentWpms: number[] } and renders the gauge + sparkline + tip. It must be purely presentational — computing WPM = wordCount / (elapsedSeconds/60), updated via a 250ms interval while isRecording. Wire it into Conversation.tsx near the user input area: capture recognition start time, pass live transcript, and on turn submit push the final wpm into a useState array also persisted to localStorage under key 'conv_pacing_wpms_v1' (cap length 5). Hide entirely on devices without speech recognition or in chat-only mode (mirror existing `recognitionSupported` checks).\n\nAdd unit tests in frontend/src/__tests__/ReplyPacingMeter.test.tsx covering: (1) renders nothing when not recording and no transcript, (2) shows correct zone color for slow/natural/rushed sample wpms, (3) renders correct tip text given a final wpm prop, (4) sparkline renders the right number of points from recentWpms.\n\nWhy: pacing is a top fluency signal beginners struggle with; a live ambient gauge nudges users toward natural rhythm without interrupting the conversation flow. It is outside the Quick Practice Hub, builds on existing speech-recognition infrastructure, and ships entirely on the frontend with no API or DB changes.",
