  "description": "Add a Filler-Word Tracker to the Conversation feature so learners get immediate, visible feedback on disfluencies (a key fluency metric for spoken English). NO schema changes required — counts are computed from existing user `messages.content` text on the fly.\n\nBackend (app/routers/conversation.py):\n1. Add a small helper `count_fillers(text: str) -> dict` (place near `_compute_pace_wpm`) that lowercases the text, tokenizes on word boundaries, and counts a fixed set of common English fillers/discourse markers: single-word {\"um\",\"uh\",\"er\",\"ah\",\"hmm\",\"like\",\"basically\",\"actually\",\"literally\",\"so\"} and multi-word phrases {\"you know\",\"i mean\",\"sort of\",\"kind of\"} (use regex with word boundaries; multi-word matched first). Return `{\"total\": int, \"breakdown\": {filler: count}}` (omit zero-count entries from breakdown). The `\"so\"`/`\"like\"`/`\"actually\"` etc. are common fillers but also legitimate words — count them only when they appear as standalone tokens; document this caveat in the docstring.\n2. Extend `MessageResponse` with `fillers: dict[str, Any] | None = None` and populate it for the user's just-sent message in the POST `/api/conversation/message` handler (compute on `request.content` before persisting; only set when `total > 0`).\n3. In the POST `/api/conversation/end` summary builder, aggregate filler counts across all stored user messages for that conversation (loop over `conv_dal.list_messages` rows where `role='user'`) and add `fillers_total: int`, `fillers_breakdown: dict[str,int]`, `fillers_per_message: float` to the returned summary dict (alongside existing fields). This works without DB migration because we recompute from `content` text.\n\nFrontend (frontend/src/pages/ConversationPage.tsx — or whichever component renders the conversation chat & summary; locate via grep for MessageResponse/feedback rendering):\n4. When a user message comes back with `fillers.total > 0`, render a small subtle badge under that user bubble like `🗣 3 fillers (um×2, like×1)` (tooltip shows full breakdown). Use existing badge/tag styles for consistency with pace_wpm display.\n5. In the conversation summary view, add a \"Filler words\" stat card showing total count, per-message average, and the top 3 fillers; include a one-line tip when the total is high (>5 in conversation): \"Try pausing silently instead of saying 'um' — it sounds more confident.\"\n\nTests:\n6. Add `tests/unit/test_conversation_fillers.py` covering `count_fillers`: empty string → 0; \"Um, I think, like, that's actually true\" → correct counts; case-insensitive; multi-word \"you know\" counted as one filler not two; word-boundary safety (\"likely\" should NOT match \"like\", \"sometimes\" should not match \"so\"/\"time\").\n7. Add an integration test in `tests/integration/test_conversation_api.py` (or the existing conversation test file) that posts a user message containing fillers and asserts `fillers.total` and `fillers.breakdown` are present in the response, and that `/end` summary contains `fillers_total` aggregating across messages.\n\nWhy: Fluency-focused, user-facing, low-risk (no schema/migration), measurable (counts), and complements existing pace_wpm and shadowing features. Helps users self-correct speech habits in real time.",
  "files_to_modify": [
