{
  "type": "feature",
  "title": "Quick Contrastive Stress card: shift word emphasis to change meaning",
  "description": "Add a new Quick Practice card that trains contrastive (emphatic) stress — moving stress to different words in the SAME sentence to convey different implied meanings (e.g., 'I didn't say HE broke it' vs 'I didn't say he BROKE it'). This is distinct from the existing QuickSentenceStressCard (which trains natural content-word stress) because it teaches how stress placement changes pragmatic meaning, a key listening + speaking skill.\n\n## UX Flow\n1. Card loads a short ambiguous sentence (5-9 words) plus 3-4 candidate stress positions, each paired with an implied meaning. Example: sentence='I didn't say he stole the car', positions=[{word:'I', meaning:'Someone else said it'}, {word:'say', meaning:\"I didn't actually say it (maybe implied)\"}, {word:'he', meaning:'Someone else stole it'}, {word:'stole', meaning:'He did something else with it'}, {word:'car', meaning:'He stole something else'}].\n2. **Listen phase**: TTS plays the sentence with one stressed word (using SSML <emphasis level='strong'>WORD</emphasis> or capitalized fallback via rate/pitch tweak around the target word). User picks the implied meaning from the choices (multiple-choice, 4 options).\n3. **Speak phase**: User is given a target meaning ('Now say it so it means: Someone else stole it') and must record themselves emphasizing the correct word. Use Web Speech Recognition + a simple heuristic on volume/duration of the target word in the transcript timing (or just check transcript correctness + show the target word highlighted as guidance — speech timing is hard, so v1 can rely on self-rating + replay).\n4. **Feedback**: Show user's recording transcript, the target stress word highlighted, and a 'Compare' button that re-plays the model TTS with stress on that word. Score: +1 for correct listening identification, +1 for completing the speaking attempt.\n\n## Backend\nAdd `app/routers/contrastive_stress.py` with:\n- `GET /api/quick/contrastive-stress?difficulty=beginner|intermediate|advanced` → returns `{sentence: str, options: [{word: str, word_index: int, meaning: str}], correct_index: int (which word is currently stressed in the audio)}`. Generated via Copilot LLM call with a prompt that asks for an ambiguous sentence + 4 distinct contrastive-stress interpretations, with one randomly chosen as the spoken target.\n- Cache last 20 generated sentences in memory to keep latency low and avoid duplicates within a session.\n- Add to `app/main.py` router registration.\n\n## Frontend\n- New `frontend/src/components/QuickContrastiveStressCard.tsx` (~250 lines) following the pattern of QuickSentenceStressCard.\n- Add API helpers `getContrastiveStress()` in `frontend/src/api.ts`.\n- Register the card in `frontend/src/components/QuickPracticeHub.tsx` with icon (lucide `Megaphone` or `Volume2`) and label 'Contrastive Stress'.\n\n## Tests\n- Unit test the router with FastAPI TestClient (mock Copilot) verifying response shape and that `correct_index` is within bounds of `options`.\n- Component test for QuickContrastiveStressCard: renders sentence after fetch, clicking a meaning marks answered, speak phase appears after correct selection.\n\n## No schema changes required (results not persisted in v1; can be added later via existing quick_practice tracking if desired).",
